WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.450 --> 00:00:06.700
CHRIS DIBONA: Please mute your
phones for the spectacular

00:00:06.700 --> 00:00:08.970
event that is forthcoming.

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:10.085
You should do that, too.

00:00:10.085 --> 00:00:10.935
NEIL GAIMAN: Yeah, OK.

00:00:10.935 --> 00:00:11.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.726
CHRIS DIBONA: It's
a BlackBerry.

00:00:13.726 --> 00:00:16.970
That was a Google, sort of
Android joke, there.

00:00:16.970 --> 00:00:18.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:18.810 --> 00:00:21.010
CHRIS DIBONA: Have I not given
you enough Androids?

00:00:21.010 --> 00:00:22.590
NEIL GAIMAN: You've
given me wonderful

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:23.830
Androids in the past.

00:00:23.830 --> 00:00:25.140
CHRIS DIBONA: You can
still have them.

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:26.450
You want a Nexus 10?

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:27.330
You know, I can--

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:27.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:27.770 --> 00:00:29.320
CHRIS DIBONA: You know,
I've got one.

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:30.310
I'll have one brought over.

00:00:30.310 --> 00:00:31.640
NEIL GAIMAN: Let me talk about
the advantages of the

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:34.513
BlackBerry when it comes
to social media.

00:00:34.513 --> 00:00:35.986
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:35.986 --> 00:00:37.715
NEIL GAIMAN: Also, the flicking
things around with

00:00:37.715 --> 00:00:38.240
your thumb.

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:39.290
I actually like flicking.

00:00:39.290 --> 00:00:39.790
CHRIS DIBONA: Yeah,
it's flicky.

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:41.342
NEIL GAIMAN: I like that.

00:00:41.342 --> 00:00:45.170
CHRIS DIBONA: So as you know,
Neil came up from Los Angeles

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:46.020
was your last stop?

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:48.820
NEIL GAIMAN: It was, last
night we finished--

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:51.640
I say "we," because there's a
well-oiled machine on either

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.890
side of me, pushing books on one
side and putting pens in

00:00:54.890 --> 00:00:57.990
and out of my hands
in the other--

00:00:57.990 --> 00:01:00.530
and we wrapped at about quarter

00:01:00.530 --> 00:01:01.370
to 3:00 in the morning.

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:04.019
CHRIS DIBONA: Wow.

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:05.730
Is that in Los Angeles
time zone?

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:07.240
It's a little different there.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:07.725
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:07.725 --> 00:01:10.601
NEIL GAIMAN: How far
away are you?

00:01:10.601 --> 00:01:11.560
CHRIS DIBONA: Me personally?

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:13.610
No, OK.

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:17.350
So, long bus trip, magical,
through the Coalinga's smell.

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:18.070
Or did you take 101?

00:01:18.070 --> 00:01:18.980
NEIL GAIMAN: I slept.

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:21.065
I don't know where
the bus drivers--

00:01:21.065 --> 00:01:22.190
there are two of them.

00:01:22.190 --> 00:01:29.300
Their names are Charlie and
Paul, and somehow you get in

00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:32.240
the bus, you fall asleep, you
wake up in the next place.

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:32.910
CHRIS DIBONA: It's like
teleportation.

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:35.470
NEIL GAIMAN: Its magic.

00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:38.520
I think they just roll the world
under the bus wheels.

00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:39.410
The bus stays completely
still.

00:01:39.410 --> 00:01:41.810
CHRIS DIBONA: Maybe the bus
stays the same, everything

00:01:41.810 --> 00:01:44.630
changes around it.

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:48.830
So I'm going to let you do your
reading, and then we'll--

00:01:48.830 --> 00:01:49.890
NEIL GAIMAN: Tell
them who I am.

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:50.665
They don't know.

00:01:50.665 --> 00:01:51.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:52.335
NEIL GAIMAN: They're
all sitting here

00:01:52.335 --> 00:01:53.560
going who is this person?

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:54.335
Why are we doing this?

00:01:54.335 --> 00:01:55.850
CHRIS DIBONA: I'm sorry.

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:57.800
I'd like to introduce
Dan Brown.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:04.170
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:07.110
CHRIS DIBONA: I was told the
number one New York Times best

00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:10.800
selling author would be on
stage, and I just assumed--

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:12.730
oh no, it's you this
week, right?

00:02:12.730 --> 00:02:13.700
Yeah, OK.

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:14.997
So, congratulations.

00:02:14.997 --> 00:02:20.601
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

00:02:20.601 --> 00:02:21.900
CHRIS DIBONA: It's you, Miss.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:23.150
Evanovich.

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:27.970
It's Neil Gaiman, as you know.

00:02:27.970 --> 00:02:28.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:31.130
CHRIS DIBONA: Not really
Janet Evanovich

00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:32.490
NEIL GAIMAN: Half the dozen
people [? walking. ?]

00:02:32.490 --> 00:02:34.670
CHRIS DIBONA: Or the one
who does the "Z As In

00:02:34.670 --> 00:02:37.570
Zebra" crime novels.

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:39.970
She's wrapping it up, too.

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:44.100
I'm sure she'll be number one
at some point, right?

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.060
Not Sookie Stackhouse,
but the other one?

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:47.625
NEIL GAIMAN: Dying
here, Chris.

00:02:47.625 --> 00:02:48.776
Dying on stage.

00:02:48.776 --> 00:02:50.800
CHRIS DIBONA: They're not
here to listen to me!

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:51.460
They here to listen to you.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:52.730
So we should let you--

00:02:52.730 --> 00:02:53.960
you had something you
wanted to read from.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:55.120
NEIL GAIMAN: I have a
couple of things I

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.470
want to read to them.

00:02:56.470 --> 00:03:01.440
I have a plan, a secret,
sort of weird plan.

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.930
So, plan.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:09.920
I'll do a little reading, and
then last time I came in and

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:12.480
did a Google Talk, and the time
I came in before that, I

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:14.880
actually got up and just burbled
for a long time, and

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:17.330
then to questions.

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:19.600
Let us assume no burblage.

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:21.620
We will go straight
to questions.

00:03:21.620 --> 00:03:22.670
There's a lot of you.

00:03:22.670 --> 00:03:27.950
We'll do a bunch of questions,
and then I will read something

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:32.620
else that won't be out for a
while, so you get a sort of

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:35.680
sneak Googly preview.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:36.810
So that's the plan.

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:37.660
CHRIS DIBONA: OK.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:38.270
You're being recorded.

00:03:38.270 --> 00:03:38.990
You're OK with that?

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:39.780
NEIL GAIMAN: What!

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:40.570
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:42.350
CHRIS DIBONA: Because I
don't want to ruin the

00:03:42.350 --> 00:03:44.232
surprise of a book.

00:03:44.232 --> 00:03:46.300
NEIL GAIMAN: Actually,
the last time I did

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:48.912
one of these, I was--

00:03:48.912 --> 00:03:51.201
CHRIS DIBONA: A younger man.

00:03:51.201 --> 00:03:53.790
NEIL GAIMAN: Younger,
significantly more beautiful,

00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:55.280
definitely less gray.

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:59.330
And in a terrible, terribly
weird mood, because as I was

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:02.920
coming in through that door, I
got the email saying, your cat

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:06.376
just bit a kid and that is going
to have to be put down.

00:04:06.376 --> 00:04:07.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:07.070 --> 00:04:08.820
NEIL GAIMAN: Oh, not my cat!

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:11.450
CHRIS DIBONA: I didn't think a
puma was a good choice for a

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:12.725
domestic animal.

00:04:12.725 --> 00:04:14.620
NEIL GAIMAN: Just large,
black, and evil.

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:16.839
And actually, having
nine lives, he

00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:19.940
escaped that, that doom.

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:23.840
So it's nice to be here at
Google, in the same place

00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:26.630
without worrying about
cat death.

00:04:26.630 --> 00:04:28.270
Hello.

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:29.000
Go and sit down or something.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.800
CHRIS DIBONA: Yeah, I'm going
to get out of the way.

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:35.520
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:36.390
NEIL GAIMAN: Right.

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:40.340
So for any of you who do
not know who I am, my

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:41.820
name is Neil Gaiman.

00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:42.990
I'm a writer.

00:04:42.990 --> 00:04:45.620
I started out writing comics.

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:46.820
Actually, no, I started
before that.

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:51.230
I was a journalist, and then I
wrote comic books back when

00:04:51.230 --> 00:04:52.540
they were still comic
books, before we

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.470
called the graphic novels.

00:04:55.470 --> 00:05:00.070
And then I started writing book
books, and somewhere in

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:04.950
there, I made some television,
and some films,

00:05:04.950 --> 00:05:06.200
and children's books.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:13.460
Probably the most fun I've had
on this signing tour that I'm

00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:17.210
on so far, which is my last
signing tour, is counting the

00:05:17.210 --> 00:05:19.460
number of licensed,
as opposed to

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:21.290
unlicensed, Doctor Who t-shirts.

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:22.646
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:22.646 --> 00:05:28.350
NEIL GAIMAN: It's currently
running at 4,000 to 6.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:30.190
I was amazed to see a licensed
t-shirt last

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:31.440
night in Los Angeles.

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:39.400
So, I wrote a couple of episodes
of "Doctor Who," and

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:45.890
most recently, I wrote
a novel accidentally.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:47.820
And that's this.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:50.820
And it's called "The Ocean at
the End of the Lane," and

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:54.830
right now, it's at number one
on the "New York Times"

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:56.570
bestseller list.

00:05:56.570 --> 00:06:02.550
And it's getting me the best
reviews of my life, which has

00:06:02.550 --> 00:06:07.440
not been a life entirely
devoid of good reviews.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:11.100
But I've never seen anything
like this.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:18.720
And the book is completely
and utterly accidental.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:29.420
It began about 18 months ago
when my wife, Amanda, who is a

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:33.870
musician and performer, went off
to Melbourne, Australia,

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:36.120
to make an album.

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:38.920
And I missed her.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.480
And I discovered that if you
have a wife who's making an

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:45.170
album, she doesn't have
much attention for

00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:48.090
anything else in the world.

00:06:48.090 --> 00:06:52.080
I would get a daily text saying,
"I love you, making an

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:54.590
album."

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:59.250
And as far as she was concerned,
that was it.

00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:00.300
She was doing her duty.

00:07:00.300 --> 00:07:02.790
And as far as I was concerned,
it was I miss you, where did

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:05.060
you go, I had a wife, I had a
girlfriend before that, I had

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:06.050
a fiance before that.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:07.670
Before that I had a girlfriend,
and now I have

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:09.575
somebody making an album.

00:07:09.575 --> 00:07:11.630
NEIL GAIMAN: And I
thought, right, I

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:15.420
will write her something.

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:22.830
And the idea of essentially sort
of sending her a short

00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:26.720
story was one that seemed
like a really good idea.

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:36.520
She's not actually--

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:41.440
this may seem strange because I
am probably best known as a

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:43.530
writer of the fantastic--

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:47.550
but my wife doesn't really
like fantasy very much.

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:51.170
So I thought, well, OK, I can
dial down the fantasy, and

00:07:51.170 --> 00:07:53.160
I'll put in things she likes.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:54.506
And she likes me.

00:07:54.506 --> 00:07:56.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:59.370
NEIL GAIMAN: So I'll put
some me in there.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:05.252
And she likes honesty, and
she likes feelings.

00:08:05.252 --> 00:08:09.460
And I don't normally do
feelings, because I'm male.

00:08:09.460 --> 00:08:11.332
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:11.332 --> 00:08:12.460
NEIL GAIMAN: And English.

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:14.132
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:14.132 --> 00:08:17.110
NEIL GAIMAN: A killer
combination.

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:20.290
But I thought, OK, I'll do a
short story, and it'll have

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:22.120
that stuff.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:23.820
And I'll set it--

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:28.250
it won't quite be my family,
and it won't actually be

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:30.700
autobiographical, but the kid,
the viewpoint character, is

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:32.320
going to be very much me.

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:35.090
And I will have some fun with
this, and I'll write her a

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:37.539
short story.

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:42.200
And after a few weeks, I went,
you know, I'm really not

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:43.904
writing a short story here.

00:08:43.904 --> 00:08:47.810
I'm probably writing
a novelette.

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:52.000
There are about sort of 10,000
to 18,000 words, maybe 10,000

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.570
to 14,000 words, something
like that.

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:59.420
And then I thought, OK, well,
a week or so later, I'm

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:00.910
obviously writing a novella.

00:09:03.455 --> 00:09:09.660
And I wrote an email to my
editors, and I said I'm

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:10.430
writing a novella.

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:12.160
Don't really know what we'll
do with it, but there is a

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.550
novella happening.

00:09:14.550 --> 00:09:17.640
And my plan had originally been
to finish the thing and

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:22.210
send it to Amanda in Melbourne,
but she finished

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:23.370
making her album.

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:27.070
And she came back to America,
and she went to Dallas to mix

00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:30.360
the album, so I went to
Dallas to be with her.

00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:33.360
And every day she'd mix her
album, and every day I would

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:38.780
go to a local coffee shop, and
I finished writing my book on

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:42.380
the first day, and then
I started typing.

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:45.000
And I typed it out.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.270
Every night, I'd
read it to her.

00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:50.020
And every morning, I'd say, OK,
where do you remember up

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:51.140
to before you fell asleep?

00:09:51.140 --> 00:09:55.130
And she'd tell me, and
I'd read it again.

00:09:55.130 --> 00:10:00.200
And when I finished, I did
a would count, because

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:03.490
technology allows you to do that
these days very simply.

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:08.770
And sent a very surprised email,
slightly apologetic

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:12.620
email, to my editors on each
side of the Atlantic saying I

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:15.970
appear to have accidentally
written a novel.

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:16.856
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:16.856 --> 00:10:18.532
NEIL GAIMAN: I'm very sorry.

00:10:18.532 --> 00:10:20.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:21.890
NEIL GAIMAN: And I'd never
written a novel that hadn't

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:22.480
been planned before.

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:25.130
I'd always known that I was
writing something, and I knew

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:26.245
that it was happening.

00:10:26.245 --> 00:10:30.950
And here I was with
an extra book.

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:36.640
And didn't actually think that
it was anything other than

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:43.300
this weird, kind of very
personal book.

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:47.680
I'd written things over the
years, mostly short stores, a

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:48.980
few graphic novels--

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:52.570
"Violent Cases," "Mr. Punch"
were both graphic novels--

00:10:52.570 --> 00:10:57.410
a few short stories, which would
all be these kind of

00:10:57.410 --> 00:11:01.040
peculiar, not really
autobiographical stories, but

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:07.310
using big, chunky
autobiographical elements.

00:11:07.310 --> 00:11:15.660
And generally speaking, they got
nice critical response and

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:19.350
sank without trace, were never
really heard of again.

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.220
And suddenly I'd written
something, and I'd send it out

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:24.900
to friends to read and give
me their reactions.

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:27.680
And they'd email back saying
it's the best thing you've

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:30.030
written, and I cried.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:31.760
And I go, OK, it must
be the feelings.

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:35.954
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:35.954 --> 00:11:39.920
NEIL GAIMAN: So, I'm going to
read you just a little bit of

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:43.580
this, because I know we have
limited time, and Chris and I

00:11:43.580 --> 00:11:47.350
took up most of it doing
possibly the worst comedy

00:11:47.350 --> 00:11:49.890
routine ever seen in this
entire building.

00:12:02.852 --> 00:12:06.830
"Nobody came to my seventh
birthday party.

00:12:06.830 --> 00:12:09.490
There was a table laid with
jellies and trifles with a

00:12:09.490 --> 00:12:12.370
party hat beside each place and
a birthday cake with seven

00:12:12.370 --> 00:12:15.120
candles on it in the center
of the table.

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:18.750
The cake had a book drawn
on it in icing.

00:12:18.750 --> 00:12:21.120
My mother, who had organized
the party, told me that the

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:23.790
lady at the bakery said they'd
never put a book on a birthday

00:12:23.790 --> 00:12:26.630
cake before, and that mostly for
boys, it was footballs or

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:27.740
spaceships.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:30.530
I was their first book.

00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.820
When it became obvious that
nobody was coming, my mother

00:12:33.820 --> 00:12:37.510
lit the seven candles on the
cake, and I blew them out.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:40.500
I ate a slice of the cake, as
did my little sister and one

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:43.350
of her friends, both of them
attending the party as

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:48.070
observers, not participants,
before they fled, giggling, to

00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:50.400
the garden.

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:53.270
Party games had been prepared
by my mother, but because

00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:55.960
nobody was there, not even my
sister, none of the party

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:56.740
games were played.

00:12:56.740 --> 00:12:58.830
And I unwrapped the newspaper
around the [? past ?] the

00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:04.690
parcel gift myself, revealing a
blue plastic Batman figure.

00:13:04.690 --> 00:13:08.230
I was sad that nobody had come
to my party, but happy that I

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:11.570
had a Batman figure, and there
was a birthday present waiting

00:13:11.570 --> 00:13:13.930
to be read, a boxed set
of the Narnia books,

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:15.870
which I took upstairs.

00:13:15.870 --> 00:13:19.930
I lay on the bed and lost
myself in the stories.

00:13:19.930 --> 00:13:21.540
I liked that.

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:24.370
Books were safer than other
people, anyway.

00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:29.980
My parents had also given me a
"Best of Gilbert and Sullivan"

00:13:29.980 --> 00:13:32.310
LP to add to the two
that I already had.

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:34.760
I'd loved Gilbert and Sullivan
since I was three when my

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:36.860
father's younger sister,
my aunt, took me to see

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:41.780
"Iolanthe" play filled with
loads and fairies.

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:44.280
I found the existence in nature
of the fairies easier

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:46.880
to understand than that
of the lords.

00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:52.720
My aunt had died soon after of
pneumonia in the hospital.

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:55.250
That evening, my father arrived
home from work, and he

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:57.640
brought a cardboard
box with him.

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:00.080
In the cardboard box was a
soft-haired, black kitten of

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:04.140
uncertain gender whom I
immediately named Fluffy and

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:08.400
which I loved utterly
and wholeheartedly.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:10.490
Fluffy slept on my
bed at night.

00:14:10.490 --> 00:14:12.760
I talked to it sometimes when
my little sister was not

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:15.610
around, half expecting it to
answer in a human tongue.

00:14:15.610 --> 00:14:17.300
It never did.

00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:18.390
I did not mind.

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:20.930
The kitten was affectionate,
and interested, and a good

00:14:20.930 --> 00:14:23.690
companion for someone who's
seventh birthday party had

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:26.740
consisted of a table with iced
biscuits and a blancmange and

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:31.260
cake and 15 folding chairs.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:33.820
I do not remember ever asking
any of the other children in

00:14:33.820 --> 00:14:37.280
my class at school why they'd
not come to my party.

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:38.560
I did not need to ask them.

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:40.760
They were not my friends,
after all.

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:43.430
They were just the people
I went to school with.

00:14:43.430 --> 00:14:46.730
I made friends slowly
when I made them.

00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:48.730
I had books, and now
I had my kitten.

00:14:48.730 --> 00:14:51.160
We would be Dick Whittington
and his cat, I knew.

00:14:51.160 --> 00:14:53.530
Of if Fluffy proved particularly
intelligent, we

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:56.580
would be the Miller's son
and Puss in Boots.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:14:59.300
The kitten slept on my pillow,
and it even waited for me to

00:14:59.300 --> 00:15:01.960
come home from school sitting on
the driveway in front of my

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:05.470
house by the fence, until a
month later it was run over

00:15:05.470 --> 00:15:09.960
the taxi that brought the opal
miner to stay at my house.

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:11.770
I was not there when
it happened.

00:15:11.770 --> 00:15:13.920
I got home from school that
day, and my kitten was not

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:14.960
waiting to meet me.

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:17.775
In the kitchen was a tall, rangy
man with tanned skin and

00:15:17.775 --> 00:15:19.120
a checked shirt.

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:21.560
He was drinking coffee
at the kitchen table.

00:15:21.560 --> 00:15:23.050
I could smell it.

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:25.830
In those days all coffee was
instant coffee, a bitter, dark

00:15:25.830 --> 00:15:28.682
brown powder that came
out of a jar.

00:15:28.682 --> 00:15:31.690
'I'm afraid I had a little
accident arriving here,' he

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:32.610
told me cheerfully.

00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:36.510
'But not to worry.' His accent
was clicked, unfamiliar.

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:39.460
It was the first South African
accent I'd had.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:42.496
He too had a cardboard box on
the table in front of him.

00:15:42.496 --> 00:15:46.220
'The black kitten, was
he yours?' he asked.

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:49.660
'It's called Fluffy,' I said.

00:15:49.660 --> 00:15:51.410
'Yeah, like I said, accident
coming here.

00:15:51.410 --> 00:15:52.940
Not to worry, disposed
of the corpse.

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:54.230
Don't have to trouble
yourself.

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:54.860
Dealt with the matter.

00:15:54.860 --> 00:15:56.600
Open the box.

00:15:56.600 --> 00:15:58.250
'What?'

00:15:58.250 --> 00:16:00.100
He pointed to the box.

00:16:00.100 --> 00:16:02.296
'Open it,' he said.

00:16:02.296 --> 00:16:04.690
The opal miner was a tall man.

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:07.100
He wore jeans and checked shirts
every time I saw him

00:16:07.100 --> 00:16:08.090
except the last.

00:16:08.090 --> 00:16:11.080
He had a thick chain of pale
gold around his neck.

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:14.280
That was gone the last
time I saw him, too.

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:16.250
I did not want to
open his box.

00:16:16.250 --> 00:16:17.440
I wanted to go off on my own.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:20.020
I wanted to cry for my kitten,
but I could not do that if

00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:22.220
anyone else was there
and watching me.

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:23.580
I wanted to mourn.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:26.170
I wanted to bury my friend at
the bottom of the garden, past

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:28.890
the green grass fairy ring into
the rhododendron bush

00:16:28.890 --> 00:16:32.110
cave, back past the heap of
grass cuttings where nobody

00:16:32.110 --> 00:16:34.550
ever went but me.

00:16:34.550 --> 00:16:36.550
The box moved.

00:16:36.550 --> 00:16:38.660
'Bought it for you,"
said the man.

00:16:38.660 --> 00:16:41.390
'Always pay my debts."

00:16:41.390 --> 00:16:44.160
I reached out, lifted the top
flap of the box, wondering if

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:46.870
this was a joke, if my kitten
would be in there.

00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:50.300
Instead a ginger face stared
up at me truculently.

00:16:50.300 --> 00:16:55.100
The opal miner took the
cat out of the box.

00:16:55.100 --> 00:16:58.942
He was a huge, ginger-striped
tomcat missing half an ear.

00:16:58.942 --> 00:17:01.070
He glared at me angrily.

00:17:01.070 --> 00:17:04.190
This cat had not liked
being put in a box.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:06.560
He was not used to boxes.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.280
I reached out to stroke his head
feeling unfaithful to the

00:17:09.280 --> 00:17:11.869
memory of my kitten, but he
pulled back so I could not

00:17:11.869 --> 00:17:14.470
touch him, and he hissed at me,
then stalked off to a far

00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:19.986
corner of the room where he sat,
and looked, and hated.

00:17:19.986 --> 00:17:24.140
'There you go, cat for a cat,"
said the opal miner, and he

00:17:24.140 --> 00:17:26.430
ruffled my hair with
his leathery hand.

00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:28.339
Then he walked out into the
hall, leaving me in the

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:32.110
kitchen with a cat that
was not my kitten.

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:35.011
The man put his head back
through the door.

00:17:35.011 --> 00:17:39.050
'He's called Monster,'
he said.

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:42.370
It felt like a bad joke.

00:17:42.370 --> 00:17:45.890
I propped open the kitchen door
so the cat could get out,

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:47.970
then I went up to the bedroom,
and lay on my bed, and cried

00:17:47.970 --> 00:17:49.860
for dead Fluffy.

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:51.990
When my parents got home that
evening, I do not think my

00:17:51.990 --> 00:17:53.290
kitten was

00:17:53.290 --> 00:18:03.417
even mentioned." [APPLAUSE]

